Humanistic Buddhism  is a modern philosophy that integrates Buddhist teachings with humanistic values, emphasizing the importance of human dignity, compassion, and the pursuit of happiness through reason and scientific method. It seeks to bridge the gap between spirituality and modern life, offering a relevant and actionable worldview that encourages individuals to cultivate mindfulness, empathy, and ethical awareness in their daily lives.
Humanistic Buddhism is based on six core teachings of the Buddha, aiming to alleviate suffering through the cultivation of mindfulness, ethical conduct, and loving-kindness.
Humanistic Buddhism for Social Well-Being: An Overview Humanistic Buddhism, also known as Engaged Buddhism, is a modern interpretation of Buddhist teachings that emphasizes the application of Buddhist concepts to address social, political, and environmental issues, aiming to promote the well-being and happiness of individuals and society as a whole. It encourages followers to take an active role in improving the world around them, rather than retreating from society.
